  "description": "Coffee Leaf Miner is a small insect pest, specifically the larva of a tiny moth (*Leucoptera coffeella*). It attacks Philippine coffee plants by tunneling and feeding inside the leaves, creating distinctive 'mines'. This pest significantly reduces the plant's ability to photosynthesize, leading to premature leaf drop, weakened trees, and substantial yield losses if left unchecked.",
  "symptoms": [
    "Irregular, winding, silvery-white tunnels or 'mines' visible on the upper surface of coffee leaves, often starting from the midrib.",
    "Brownish blotches or necrotic areas forming around the mines as the damaged tissue dies.",
    "Premature yellowing and dropping of affected leaves, especially older ones, even during dry periods.",
    "Stunted growth and reduced vigor of the coffee plant due to significant defoliation and stress."
  ],
  "causes": [
    "The primary cause is the larva of the Coffee Leaf Miner moth, *Leucoptera coffeella*.",
    "Prolonged dry spells and high temperatures, common in the Davao Region, favor the rapid multiplication and spread of the pest.",
    "Weakened or stressed coffee plants due to poor nutrition, lack of proper pruning, or other diseases are more susceptible to severe infestations."
  ],
  "diagnosis": "Your coffee plants are experiencing a severe infestation of Coffee Leaf Miners, meaning a large portion of your leaves are heavily damaged. If left untreated, this will lead to widespread defoliation, significantly reduced photosynthesis, stunted growth, and eventually, a drastic drop in coffee bean yield and quality. The plants will become very weak and susceptible to other pests and diseases.",
  "urgency": "Critical",
  "urgency_reason": "A 'Severe' Miner infestation requires immediate and decisive action to prevent widespread damage, significant yield loss, and potential death of young trees.",
  "farmer_summary": "You are dealing with a serious Coffee Leaf Miner problem that is severely damaging your coffee leaves. This will greatly reduce your harvest if not addressed quickly. The most important thing to do right now is to immediately remove and destroy all heavily infested leaves to reduce the pest population.",
  "immediate_actions": [
    "**Handpick and Destroy Infested Leaves:** Immediately walk through your farm and manually pick off all coffee leaves showing severe mining damage. Collect these leaves in a sack and bury them deep or burn them far from the farm to kill the larvae inside.",
    "**Prepare a Basic Soap Solution:** Mix 1 tablespoon of dishwashing liquid (like Joy or Axion) with 1 liter of water. This can be used as a temporary contact spray on lightly affected leaves to suffocate some larvae and deter adult moths. Spray directly onto the leaves, especially the undersides.",
    "**Prune and Sanitize:** Prune any dead, dying, or heavily infested branches. Ensure good air circulation within the canopy. Collect all pruned materials and leaf litter around the base of the trees and dispose of them properly (bury or burn) to remove potential breeding grounds."
  ],
  "treatment_protocol": [
    {
      "step": "Intensive Sanitation and Pruning",
      "detail": "Continue handpicking and destroying severely mined leaves daily for the first few days. Prune affected branches to open up the canopy and remove heavily damaged parts. This reduces the pest population and improves spray penetration. Ensure all debris is removed from the farm."
    },
    {
      "step": "Organic Spray Application (First Line)",
      "detail": "Prepare a strong Neem oil solution (e.g., 5-10ml pure Neem oil per liter of water, add a few drops of dish soap as an emulsifier). Spray thoroughly on all affected plants, focusing on both upper and lower leaf surfaces, early in the morning or late in the afternoon. Repeat every 5-7 days for at least 3 applications. This acts as an anti-feedant and growth disruptor."
    },
    {
      "step": "Chemical Intervention (If Organic Fails or for Rapid Control)",
      "detail": "If the organic treatments are not showing significant improvement after 2 weeks, or if the infestation is spreading rapidly, consider a DA-accredited systemic insecticide. Look for products containing **Imidacloprid** (e.g., Confidor, Admire) or **Cypermethrin** (e.g., Cymbush, Ripcord) at your local agri-vet store. Follow label instructions strictly for dosage (typically 1-2 ml/L water for Imidacloprid, or 1-1.5 ml/L for Cypermethrin). Apply as a foliar spray, ensuring good coverage. Systemic insecticides are absorbed by the plant and kill larvae feeding inside the leaves. Apply only once every 2-3 weeks if necessary, alternating active ingredients to prevent resistance."
    },
    {
      "step": "Monitoring and Follow-up",
      "detail": "Continuously monitor your coffee plants for new signs of mining. Even after treatment, new generations of miners can emerge. Be prepared to re-apply organic or chemical treatments as needed, following the recommended intervals. Focus on maintaining plant health through proper fertilization and irrigation."
    }
  ],
  "organic_alternatives": [
    "**Neem Oil Extract:** Mix 5-10ml of pure Neem oil (available in agri-vet stores) with 1 liter of water. Add 5ml of liquid dish soap as an emulsifier. Shake well. Spray thoroughly on all leaf surfaces, especially the undersides, every 5-7 days. Neem acts as an anti-feedant, repellent, and growth disruptor for the larvae.",
    "**Chili-Garlic-Soap Solution:** Grind 5-10 pieces of hot chili peppers (siling labuyo) and 5-10 cloves of garlic. Soak in 1 liter of water overnight. Strain the mixture, then add 1 tablespoon of liquid dish soap. Dilute this concentrate with 5-10 liters of water. Spray directly onto affected leaves every 3-5 days. This acts as a repellent and contact irritant.",
    "**Yellow Sticky Traps (DIY):** Cut yellow plastic sheets or old yellow plastic containers. Coat them with used cooking oil or a sticky substance like petroleum jelly. Hang these traps near your coffee trees at canopy height. Adult miner moths are attracted to yellow and will get stuck, reducing the breeding population. Replace or re-coat traps regularly."
  ],
  "schedule": [
    {"day": "Day 1", "task": "Immediate handpicking and destruction of severely infested leaves. Prepare and apply basic soap solution or first organic spray (Neem/Chili-Garlic)."},
    {"day": "Day 2-3", "task": "Continue handpicking and destroying new severely infested leaves. Re-apply organic spray if rain washed off the first application. Set up DIY yellow sticky traps."},
    {"day": "Day 4-7", "task": "Second application of organic spray (Neem/Chili-Garlic).","description":"","symptoms":[],"causes":[],"treatment_protocol":[]}

